-- WP10 (docs/spec/WASM-SEMANTICS.md §1) — the CONTROL for `eager_global_string_slice.mdk`.
--
-- The same program on a LIST receiver instead of a String. `eagerVars`'s `CListSlice` arm
-- (compiler/backend/emit_support.mdk) descended `lo`/`hi` all along, so this fixture was
-- GREEN on every engine even while its String twin silently answered `hel` instead of
-- `el`. That contrast is the whole evidence for #553 Stage A: two neighbouring arms of one
-- function, identical program shape, one scanning its bounds and one not. It is what makes
-- "`CStringSlice` dropped `lo`/`hi`" a demonstrated claim rather than an argued one, and
-- it rules out every receiver-agnostic explanation (the slice syntax itself, the range
-- bound, the auto-print path, this gate's link line, the corpus).
--
-- It is also the tripwire for an over-broad fix: a change to eager-global ordering that
-- regresses the ALREADY-CORRECT case turns this red.
--
-- `main` destructures rather than indexing because this corpus's emit probe
-- (test/bin/llvm_emit_typed_main) has no `.[i]` on a List ("unbound variable 'index'") and
-- cannot auto-print an ADT — a probe limitation, not a language one. Taking the head keeps
-- the result a scalar Int while still reading THROUGH the slice, so the bound `loL` stays
-- load-bearing: were `loL` read as a still-zero cell the slice would be [10, 20] and this
-- would answer 10, not 20.
--
-- Do not merge these two fixtures into one file — the corpus is one-program-per-file, and
-- the differential compares ENGINES on the same program, not two programs against each
-- other.

srcL = [10, 20, 30, 40]

partL = srcL.[loL..3]

loL = 1

main =
  match partL
    (h :: _) => h
    [] => 0
